WEBVTT

00:00:01.080 --> 00:00:03.640
Welcome to the killer feature! Clone an

00:00:03.640 --> 00:00:06.600
entire production repo regardless of size

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:07.720
, and break nothing.

00:00:08.683 --> 00:00:11.323
One parent repo fans out into as many

00:00:11.323 --> 00:00:14.043
independent clones as you want. Each fork

00:00:14.123 --> 00:00:16.683
is its own isolated environment running

00:00:16.683 --> 00:00:18.363
side by side with the original.

00:00:19.328 --> 00:00:21.968
Think of sharing a folder link. The link is

00:00:21.968 --> 00:00:24.848
the same lightweight thing whether the folder is small

00:00:24.848 --> 00:00:27.648
or huge, and forking works on the same

00:00:27.648 --> 00:00:28.128
principle.

00:00:29.021 --> 00:00:31.981
One gigabyte, one hundred gigabytes

00:00:32.701 --> 00:00:35.261
, one terabyte: the fork behaves the

00:00:35.261 --> 00:00:38.221
same. Repo size does not factor

00:00:38.221 --> 00:00:39.341
into the equation.

00:00:42.816 --> 00:00:45.376
Now the fork. One command will clone

00:00:45.376 --> 00:00:48.416
the entire repo, the app, the database

00:00:48.816 --> 00:00:51.616
, the config files, regardless of size

00:00:52.256 --> 00:00:55.136
. One gigabyte, one hundred gigabytes, one terabyte

00:00:55.616 --> 00:00:57.856
: the size simply does not matter.

00:00:57.967 --> 00:01:00.767
Fork done. The clone is up and running, regardless

00:01:00.767 --> 00:01:01.327
of size.

00:01:04.801 --> 00:01:08.081
Both repos exist side by side now. Same

00:01:08.081 --> 00:01:11.121
machine, same disk, two completely

00:01:11.121 --> 00:01:12.561
independent environments.

00:01:15.690 --> 00:01:18.650
Two repos, one disk. Same data, separate

00:01:18.650 --> 00:01:19.370
everything else.

00:01:22.878 --> 00:01:25.758
Let us prove the isolation. In the original

00:01:25.998 --> 00:01:28.958
, our marker file is right where we left it. The

00:01:28.958 --> 00:01:31.518
fork existence did not change anything in the

00:01:31.518 --> 00:01:31.998
parent.

00:01:33.704 --> 00:01:36.344
Original file still there. The fork

00:01:36.344 --> 00:01:36.984
didn't touch it.

00:01:38.027 --> 00:01:40.827
The parent repo is the sun and your fork

00:01:41.147 --> 00:01:44.027
is a mirror catching its light. The shared base

00:01:44.027 --> 00:01:46.667
stays untouched while anything you paint

00:01:46.667 --> 00:01:48.507
on the mirror belongs only to you.

00:01:51.892 --> 00:01:54.692
Now let us delete that file, but only inside

00:01:54.692 --> 00:01:57.332
the fork. We are making a destructive change

00:01:57.332 --> 00:01:57.652
here.

00:02:00.946 --> 00:02:03.906
Gone in the fork. The original stays untouched.

00:02:07.292 --> 00:02:10.092
Back to the original. The marker file is still here

00:02:10.492 --> 00:02:13.212
, untouched. Same image, separate

00:02:13.212 --> 00:02:15.532
Docker daemons, separate filesystems.

00:02:17.230 --> 00:02:19.870
Still here. Forks are properly isolated.

00:02:23.392 --> 00:02:26.032
When you are done, just delete the fork. The

00:02:26.032 --> 00:02:29.072
original stays exactly as it was. Fork

00:02:29.472 --> 00:02:32.112
, experiment, break things, delete

00:02:32.752 --> 00:02:33.312
. No risk.

00:02:36.423 --> 00:02:39.303
Fork removed. The original is exactly

00:02:39.303 --> 00:02:39.943
as we left it.

00:02:40.973 --> 00:02:43.693
A fork is a frozen photograph of the parent

00:02:43.693 --> 00:02:46.493
at one instant. The parent keeps flowing

00:02:46.493 --> 00:02:49.613
like a river, but your snapshot stays exactly

00:02:49.613 --> 00:02:50.493
where it was.

00:02:51.386 --> 00:02:54.506
Five forks of a hundred gigabyte repo still

00:02:54.506 --> 00:02:57.066
add up to about a hundred gigabytes on disk

00:02:57.546 --> 00:03:00.266
. You only pay for the bytes you actually change inside

00:03:00.266 --> 00:03:00.826
each fork.

00:03:01.626 --> 00:03:03.987
You just saw the commands.

00:03:03.987 --> 00:03:06.348
Next we make it visual:

00:03:06.348 --> 00:03:08.237
a real database app,

00:03:08.237 --> 00:03:09.181
forked live,

00:03:09.181 --> 00:03:12.015
edited side by side — and

00:03:12.015 --> 00:03:13.904
the original never flinches.
